# redaction-policy.md template (session-handoff v0.1.0, schema 0.1)

This file is a **template**. The session-handoff skill renders it into your project space as `config/redaction-policy.md` (or `config-redaction-policy.md` on flat surfaces) on first invocation if you do not already have one. share-sanitize loads it; if absent, share-sanitize falls back to the public defaults in `references/defaults.md`.

To configure interactively, load the rendered file and tell your AI "walk me through configuring this." It runs the shared interview (`references/configure.md`), uses the FIELD GUIDE below, and writes a new version for approval before saving. Changes to redaction categories, `sensitivity_rules`, or `redaction_provider` are flagged as compliance-relevant.

This policy keys off the `compliance` taxonomy in `config/org-config.md`. The two layer; they do not duplicate. Mechanics live in `references/redaction.md`.

The rendered file is the content inside the fenced block below: everything from the `---` frontmatter through the final config key. On first run the skill auto-extracts exactly that fenced block (not this SPDX header or surrounding prose) and writes it as `config/redaction-policy.md`. To do it by hand, copy everything inside the fence into `config/redaction-policy.md`:

```yaml
---
schema_version: "0.1"
_managed_by: session-handoff-skill
config_type: redaction-policy
config_editable: true
configure_with: references/configure.md
---
# To configure: load this file and tell your AI "walk me through configuring this."
# It runs the shared interview (references/configure.md), uses the FIELD GUIDE below,
# and writes a new version of this file for approval before saving.
#
# ============================================================
# session-handoff - redaction policy (v0.1.0, schema 0.1)
# ============================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: redaction_provider  (COMPLIANCE-RELEVANT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# The seam, not the engine. share-sanitize runs against a stable
# contract (in: handoff + policy; out: redacted copy + manifest).
#
# built-in (default): the minimal model-driven redactor runs the
#   masking and PII-flagging steps.
# document-sanitizer (reserved): when that sister skill ships,
#   set this value to route masking/flagging to it without
#   changing share-sanitize's shape.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
redaction_provider: built-in


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: pii_flagging
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Assistive PII detection. Distinct from redaction: it FLAGS for
# review, it never auto-removes, and it never claims to find all
# PII (honesty guardrail, references/redaction.md section 5).
#
# enabled: default true (the secure-by-default exception).
# categories: which PII kinds to flag.
# mode: flag-for-review only in v0.1.0.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
pii_flagging:
  enabled: true
  categories: [name, email, phone, address, gov_id, account_number]
  mode: flag-for-review


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: categories  (COMPLIANCE-RELEVANT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# The full vocabulary of redaction categories share-sanitize can
# mask. sensitivity_rules below selects which fire per sensitivity.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
categories: [pii, financials, client_names, internal_names, credentials]


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: masking_style
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# How masked spans render.
#   redact -> [REDACTED]
#   tag    -> [REDACTED:category]   (default; keeps the kind)
#   hash   -> a stable token so repeats stay co-referenced
# -----------------------------------------------------------
masking_style: tag


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: sensitivity_rules  (COMPLIANCE-RELEVANT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# The categories forced for each handoff sensitivity. share-
# sanitize masks sensitivity_rules[handoff.sensitivity] plus any
# categories named at invocation. More restrictive sensitivities
# force more categories.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
sensitivity_rules:
  open:         []
  internal:     [credentials]
  confidential: [credentials, pii, client_names]
  restricted:   [credentials, pii, client_names, financials, internal_names]


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: custom_patterns
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Optional org-specific descriptors or regex for categories the
# defaults do not cover. Empty by default. Keep descriptive.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
custom_patterns: []
```

## What does not belong in redaction-policy.md

- The compliance taxonomy itself; that lives in `config/org-config.md` and this policy keys off it.
- Secrets or credential values. Patterns describe what to redact; they do not store the secrets.

## Honesty guardrail

Redaction is assistive and model-based under `redaction_provider: built-in`. It is not guaranteed to find or remove all sensitive content. The manifest carries this disclaimer on every run, and the operator should review the redacted output before sharing. See `references/redaction.md`.
